Section1.Para:
The photocatalytic activities of TiO2 and In2O3/TiO2 are shown in Fig. 10. In2O3/TiO2 composites exhibit better photocatalytic activity than TiO2 and 5 % In possesses the best photocatalytic performance among the experimental compositions. These results suggest that loading In2O3 onto the surface of TiO2 can greatly enhance the photocatalytic activity of TiO2 and that there is an optimum loading of In2O3 on the surface of TiO2. The initial step in TiO2-mediated photocatalysis degradation is proposed to involve the generation of an e−/h+ pair, leading to the formation of hydroxyl radicals (



                ), superoxide radical anions (



                  $\mathrm{O}_{2}^{\bullet-}$
                ), and hydroperoxyl radicals (



                ). These radicals are the oxidizing species in the photocatalytic oxidation processes. The high charge-separation rate is beneficial to form the active species, which favors the photocatalytic decolorization of MO. 

